{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013g1HiaZdss5Lxc9KuB2MAE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n- CA cert and key are in `mongodb-tls-ca` secret (keys: `ca.crt` and `ca.key`)\n- Current server cert (as `server.pem`) is in `mongodb-tls-cert`\n- `openssl-toolbox` pod is available\n- 3 MongoDB pods are running (mongo-rs-0, mongo-rs-1, mongo-rs-2)\n\nThe server cert was created with `-days 2`, so it's near expiry. I need to:\n1. Use the `openssl-toolbox` pod to generate a new server certificate signed by the existing CA\n2. Make it valid for about a year\n3. Update the `mongodb-tls-cert` secret with the new cert\n4. Do a rolling restart of the MongoDB pods to pick up the new certificate without causing downtime\n\nI'll check what SANs the original cert had and generate a new one with the same identities but extended validity. From the logs, the cert includes CN=mongo-rs and SANs covering localhost, mongo, and the full DNS names for each replica set member across the cluster.\n\nNow I'll execute this: copy the CA cert and key from the secret into a working pod, generate a fresh server key and certificate signing request, sign it with the existing CA for 365 days, combine the cert and key into a single PEM file, update the secret, then restart the MongoDB StatefulSet one pod at a time.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":562,"cache_read_input_tokens":32544,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":562},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"58d7fd5f-0875-41cc-809d-20f0a4774dcb","uuid":"eb3c36bb-9cc9-453c-a42e-9382e3c2cd95","request_id":"req_011CcMs7mfsB4bqCowEje4db"}
